article.description: Allison Feaster tied her career-high with 23 points as the Charlotte Sting beat the Miami Sol 76-63 Saturday.
article.headline: Feaster sends Sol to 2-8 start
article.linkText: Feaster powers Sting past struggling Sol
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Allison Feaster's big night was enough to
extend the Charlotte Sting's home winning streak.

	   Feaster tied her career-high with 23 points Saturday as the
Sting beat the Miami Sol 76-63. It was Charlotte's franchise-record
12th straight regular season home win -- the fourth-best streak in
WNBA history.

	   Feaster, who tied a team record with five 3-pointers, has hit
nine 3s in her last two games.

	   "When I feel like I'm in the flow and rhythm, good things
happen,'' Feaster said.

	   Tammy Sutton-Brown added 14 points and nine rebounds while
Andrea Stinson had 12 points and a season-high six assists for the
Sting (5-5).

	   Betty Lennox scored 13 of her season-high 18 points in the first
half to lead Miami (2-8), while Sandy Brondello added 12 points.
Pollyanna Johns-Kimbrough grabbed a career-high 12 rebounds.

	   The Sol led by nine early in the second half, but Charlotte
rallied behind its defense.

	   Miami shot 60 percent in the first half to lead 39-31 at the
break. In the second half, the Sting forced 13 turnovers that led
to 19 points, and held the Sol to 43-percent shooting.

	   "We were a much better team in the second half than in the
first,'' Sting coach Anne Donovan said. "In the second half we
played good defense. I preach defense all the time. For us, it is
what makes our offense go.''

	   Miami led 42-33 on Brandello's three-point play early in the
second half, but Charlotte went on an 18-2 run to take the lead.
Feaster and Stinson each had seven points in the spurt.

	   Charlotte clung to a 57-56 lead with 7:12 to play when Feaster
hit her fifth 3-pointer, starting a 13-2 run. Miami got no closer
than eight points the rest of the way, losing for the third
straight game.

	   "They came after us and we couldn't stop them in the second
half,'' Miami coach Ron Rothstein said. "It's very frustrating. It
all started on the defensive end for them. It led to turnovers and
easy baskets.''
